I am thinking it is most likely the smaller tube, which you connected to the soapy water, may be too large in relation to the main line? I am not really up on my physics. I think I will add a disclaimer that it is not fully tested, or wasn't until now, to the description. I printed a few of them and never got to test them fully. Thank you for letting me know! Sorry it didn't fully work for your application.

comments.author: Linkreincarnate

comments.text:
It's used to create a pump for the second, offset fitting. Force fluid through the fitting next to the offset fitting and it should create a vacuum on the offset fitting that will draw air or another fluid into the main stream. Could potentially be used to aspirate a fluid, mix fluids, or pull a vacuum. Check out Wikipedia for info on the effect.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Venturi_effect

description.text: Finally! The square one has arrived! Have fun shuffling the shape-shifting cube to see if you have what it takes to solve it.(this cube was not colored at the time of this posting, but the square one has the same color pattern of a standard cube)

assembly is pretty straightforward. You need to print 8 small and 8 large slivers along with 2 core pieces. Once printing is finished (and slight filing), take a nail, screw, piece of filament, etc, and glue it into the hole on the inside of one of the the cores. Next, put the pieces on both sides of the cores. Lastly, use hot glue (this is important, because we don't want it to stick, just act like rubber to stop the core pieces from sliding off easily.) to glue in the other side of the shaft. Let the glue cool/dry (if you used something else to flue the first part of the shaft in), then enjoy!

This cube feels (and is) quite loose, but don't worry, if you have a somewhat decent printer, your pieces won't fall off.

description.text:
I wanted to fit a direct drive extruder and BLTouch to the HyperCube so I came up with this.
I tried to keep it as compact as possible.
The mount is for use with the latest motor from E3D or a pancake stepper such as this (http://uk.stepperonline.com/09-nema-17-bipolar-stepper-12a-11ncm156ozin-17hm081204s-p-99.html), to keep the extruder as compact as possible so as not to interfere with the drive belts or the X motor mount.
I couldn't use the fan mount as designed as it fitted in front of the Titan extruder and the XY joiner couldn't reach the Y limit switch, so the logical place for the fan was above the stepper. The fan attaches to the extruder mount with an M3 screw which screws into a M3x4mm knurl nut which is heat set into the mount. I got the knurl nuts from http://www.banggood.com/100pcs-M34mm-H62-Brass-Knurl-Nuts-DIY-Accessories-p-971077.html?rmmds=search

I've updated the fan mount to make the fan support stronger, as it's only held on with one screw.

Update: After working with the radial blower fan I found that it is a little unwieldy so I have opted to use this cooling fan by Jinx: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1693413

so I printed these, and they worked great, but now I find the vertical arm bends too much, so will look at filling in the channel,

I closed in the gap, hopefully to add strength. I have a Pro-line camera which weighs a lot more then consumer line cameras

***UPDATE 3**
I have completed the changes, and everything seems to work fine, all bolt holes and nut/head holes are now changed to hold a 1/4" bolt properly. Length of bolts depend on what equipment you have, so you will have to test that out. I used a 1" bolt to attach plate to the horizontal arm, I then used a 1 1/2" and shorter (knob13_21) knob to attach the plate socket to transversal arm, then another 1 1/2" olt to attach the transversal arm to the vertical arm with the taller (knob16_21) knob, you will need to tap the bolt into knob with hammer. title: Breadboard with 4 mm safety banana plugs

description.text:
I could not find any breadboards with safety plugs on the market - only the ones with old fashioned non-safety 4 mm banana plugs and often connectors of a poor quality. So I designed my own instead.

This item was made on a laser cutter with 4 mm plywood. The layers were stacked together and glued with normal wood glue between each layer. The holes for the small cables going from the plugs to the breadboard were drilled with a 3 mm drill.

It is designed for two 830 tie point breadboards with four 4 mm banana safety plugs, spaced the standard 19 mm apart. I have used "crystal breadboards" from Ali Express, as the quality in my experience is a bit better as the normal white breadboards.

The holes for the safety plugs are made for MultiContact XUB-G 1 ST plugs ( https://www.conrad.de/de/laborbuchse-buchse-einbau-vertikal-stift-4-mm-rot-multicontact-xub-g-1-st-735540.html ). The board is made for three different voltages with common ground.

title: Homebrew Blade Server Case - Fully printable (Mini-ITX)

description.text: Worked out that I could probably print my own blade server case add my own components and be in front over buying a blade server from a vendor.

• Modular - The case is designed so you can stack together as many as needed, and they can be secured together to move around as one unit.
    For example... I'm going to uave 2 PC's clustered and I'm probably going to have a third bay for the power supplies, and a fourth for a wi-fi router (Which should still work fine inside the case because its plastic).
  • Suitable for small printers - All the pieces fit in a 14cm x 14cm print bed, if you have a larger print bed you may be able to outershell a few pieces so there are less prints involved.
  • Easy to assemble - almost everything is held together by nilon ties (or zip ties depending on your parlance).
  • Takes a Mini-ITX board, which is about the smallest board you can get that still lets you fit your own CPU's, so you can still mix and match parts to get the machine you want.
  • There should be enough clearance on one side to fit a great honk'in fan if your CPU needs it and enough room on the otherside to fit a couple of hard disks (Initially I'm going to use USB hard disks with velcro for ease of swapping, but I'll probably deisgn a printable mount later depending on how well that works).
  • Rail system - An individual motherboard can be easily pulled out for maintenance without disturbing the remainder of the rack.

I see this as something that could easily be extended and modified to suit a number of purposes. Please feel free to modify and extend this design to suit your needs. The extensions I've made are:
  • 2.5" HDD mounts (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:197825)
  • Fan Mounts (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:184302)
    • I've also created a collection to group any enhancements together. (http://www.thingiverse.com/WHITECOAT/collections/homebrew-blade-server) If anyone else does extend this design and cares to share it let me know and I'll add it to the collection.

There is a fully assembled image in the sketch-up file as well as an exploded diagram so you can see how the pieces go together.
So, I hope it is fairly obvious from that how it goes together, but let me know if it needs clarification.

On the case most of the holes are 2mm x 3mm which should allow nilon ties to slide through easily.  If the ties don't go through due to print tolerances, you can hand drill through the holes with a 3mm drill to widen them.

The blade itself (not sure of a word for it, lets call it the part that holds the motherboard) is held together with some printable clips. It takes 8 clips to hold the whole thing together. Once in place its quite sturdy.
They are a very snug fit, but should press through the holes.
I did have to use pliers to push a couple of the clips through. A little filing with a hobby file on the holes also helps for particularly stuborn ones, but you want to keep it snug so that it is rigid after.

• There are 16 prints to do one whole bay, so it may take a while. I took a shortcut and used perspex for the side walls. But, In theory I guess it could have been done in about 24 hours if the printer was running constantly. In my case it was more like a month of Sundays.
  • until such time as you put on the outer walls it will seem flimsy. The outer walls add significanly to the structural integrity.
  • As in woodwork where the addage is that nails are primarily to hold things together while glue dries. The same would apply here, zipties hold it together initially but PVA glue would make it rock solid.
  • I'd love to see case modders do something with this. I can only imagine what you could do by combining case modding with 3d printing. If you do use this design as a base for inventing your own case, please let me know I'd love to see the result.

title: Customiser: YATNAG - Yet Another "This is Not A Thing"

description.text:
This thing is not a thing. I only made it to visualize the results of calculation for nozzle positioning as done with delta printers. As side effect, the needed elementary geometry calculations are put as functions into this source.
I uploaded it as customisable "thing" to thingiverse because I could easily add sliders for positioning that way, and play with it. Alas, what I was mostly interested in, I can't see as customiser: how do minimal elevation steps affect nozzle positioning precision. It seems obvious that precision is better in the center of printing plate, and gets worse towards both sides. This model puts the effects into - oxymoron alert - tangible numbers.

Afterthought: Output could be written into the "thing" using the "text" function of OpenSCAD - and therefore those results I wanted to look at. This was added in a recently uploaded version.

"Delta" operation is in two dimensions only, which makes calculation simple, and leaves room for thinking about a minimal mixed cartesian/delta printer, with Y axis positioning through plate movement. For what the model is meant for, it doesn't matter whether it's operating in 2D or 3D space.

Change X and Y according desired nozzle position, and see the hinges moved to their respective elevations.
I don't know about "grades" so I picked "2nd grade" Elementary geometry suffices. "Pythagoras" should have been mentioned. Power and Square roots assumed familiar with.

description.text:
This is work in progress clone of the DJI Mavic. I started this project on September 26th, the night before the official release of the Mavic. I designed it based on leaked images, and had most of the CAD for the bottom frame sections and arms (all that's needed to fly), done before the release the next morning. I tossed together a quick video showing it off, and then got to work on printing it. Fast forward to today, October 21st, and I have a flying DIY Maviclone, before the DJI Mavic has shipped. (Wouldve been sooner, but waiting on parts from China gets obnoxious ;P)
There is still a lot of work to be done. The canopy and avionics plate are made of foam board and duct tape in the build log videos 1-5 (linked below), as I wanted to wait to test fly it before continuing on the rest of the CAD (in case a major re-design was required) But everything checks out, so a proper avionics plate and battery bay are in the works, as well as I'm wanting to get some different electronics (4in1 ESC and a PXF-mini flight controller shield from ErleRobotics, to use in conjunction with a Pi Zero.)
That being said, this is the release of V1. Its not perfect, parts need sanding to fit right (intentional, need a tight fit), and while mine flies, I cannot gurantee that for yours at this stage. Files provided as-is, but open source and free of charge (however donations are GREATLY appreciated! Links to places you can support me are in the description of the build updates) See improvements that can be made? Make them and upload them as a Remix :)
Thanks for checking this out, and enjoy :)
Build Update Playlist: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLFXaMSDmL4_4_uWaUwMCM9qZoXfc4svYv

CRITICAL UPDATE 10/24/2016: BottomFrameRear STL and 123dx files were updated. The old version did not have the tabs that allow the arms to remain in the unfolded position properly, didn't notice this until today. The new version does, and the old version has been removed.

GENERAL UPDATE 11/7/2016: Uploaded the Canopy files. The canopy has extrusions to allow it to hold in place on the horizontal axis, however you will need to secure it with zipties or a velcro strap for the time being, while I decide a more appropriate method (clips would be nice, tool-less etc, however would be fragile. Might end up bolting the top and bottom together with a bolt or two, unsure.) Also uploaded a picture of the folded unit with the revised canopy and folding props installed.

UPDATE 12/10/2016: I have replaced FrontArmLeft.stl, FrontArmRight.stl, and FrontArms.123dx with updated/revised versions, as the bolt pattern for the motor was reversed. title: Mockup of the Zesty Nimble: Lightweight direct drive extruder

description.text:
The Nimble Mock-up file is a blocky version of the Nimble. The positioning of the screws is correct as is the filament and the Drive cable position. This will be the final shape. Overall it is the smallest it has ever been and I think we have reached the minimal practical shape. It is the Right hand shape. Of course in real life the Nimble is ambidextrous, it can be made to me a right handed or a left handed version. But these mock-up files do not allow for that, so we have added a left handed version as well.

The Nimble Extruder
With an installed weight of less than 27 grams on your carriage/effector the Zesty Nimble is smallest and lighest extruder you can buy, it has ample torque and is installable in multiple orientations.

The Nimble is available at: https://zesty.tech

You can eliminate the bowden cable and print any material available. It is so small, 2 easily fit on top of a Chimera or Cyclops.

We have all sorts of adapters available for different hot ends and printers. If the right adapter is not there for you, we will design a new one for you.

The Nimble adapter is the basic adapter we use to adapt to the various hot ends. We are adding a lot more adapters. Be aware that the Nimble is still being updated and the adapter can still change.

The Mount block for the Nimble is the idealised shape to lock the Nimble in place around the filament. This is the perfect shape but if it is too complex, it can be simplified. Of course the large round base is just an example of how it can be used.

description.text: This is a remix of the baton designed by sahrchitect. I recommend plating the files as they are. there is no support used. You should not have to repair any file. if you repair the baton body files then the object will no longer be hollow! after the body parts print, you will have to take a dremel and grind out each end. grind only the openings so that inside diameter is I believe 29mm.The baton body should be hollow. Do not glue the two halves yet! Take your sleeve and slide it through the two body halves. the closed end of the sleeve will be at the front upper half where the front cap will be. Open end will be at the back end of the lower half. if there is a lot of resistance then you will have to grind more material out. when the sleeve slides through then slide the shaft through aligning the tabs with the channels in the sleeve. There should be some slight resistance so that the shaft when fully assembled does not slide out back and forth. Use some filament and glue it in the channel of the sleeve at the front end of each side as a stopper for the shaft. if the shaft goes out all the way, the shaft will appear to "droop" down. glue the stoppers in a position where the shaft, when at the end of its travel, will not "droop" (1.5 inch from the end approx.). when everything looks good, glue the sleeve to the upper half. be sure not to glue the shaft!!! Slide the lower half and glue to the upper half. Grind off any excess of the back end of the sleeve. Glue the rear cap. glue the front cap to the shaft. assemble the handle halves. place handle in bracket and drill a hole through the center and add a bolt and nut with nylock. may have to grind a little to get it to clear when folding. don't force it! its plastic! sorry if it seams like a lot of work but its my first remix. Many thanks to sahrchitect.
